\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4919515 <hi rend="bold">An Island Mystery</hi>
\par 
\par On an April morning in the year 1835 the schooner Peor es Nada, of Monterey sailed out of Santa Barbara harbor on an otter-hunting. Three [There] to the lower
 California coast. Three months later the schooner unloaded her cargo of pelts in San Diego harbor, and the skipper made a bargain with the Franciscan fathers there to sail to San Nicolas, one of the Santa Barbara islands thirty miles from the coast, and 
b
ring the islanders to the mainland. Before the destination was reached a gale sprung up, and landing was effected [affected] with the greatest difficulty. No time was wasted ashore. The islanders, some twenty in number, were hurried into the boats and all
 
speed was made to reach the schooner. In the excitement and confusion a child was left behind. The mother supposed it to have been carried aboard in the arms of one of the sailors. She frantically implored the men to return. The captain said that it was i
mpossible. He did not dare risk further the lives of his charges. {\*\atrfstart 419667515}
Finding that they were going out to sea, the young mother became desperate, and, eluding the sailors, jumped overboard and struck out through the angry waters for the shore.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid7828100 
{\*\atrfend 419667515}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 419667515}{\*\atndate 1194480518}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid7828100 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7828100 Jump overboard}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4919515  No attempt was made to rescue her, and in a moment she was lost to sight in the huge waves that crashed against the rock coast.
\par 
\par The schooner weathered the storm and, after an adventurous voyage, reached San Pedro, where the islanders were landed. Some of
 them were sent by the Franciscan brothers to Los Angeles and the others were put to work in the neighboring mission of San Gabriel. It was the intention of the skipper to return to San Nicolas immediately to see if the woman or child were living; but imp
e
rative orders from the owner were received to convey at once a party of otter-hunters to Santa Rosa island and afterward to carry a cargo of lumber to San Francisco. But the Peor es Nada never made its second cruise to San Nicolas island, for on its north
ern trip the schooner capsized at the entrance to the Golden Gate. The crew were washed ashore and the schooner drifted out to sea. {\*\atrfstart 419667516}
At that time there were no other craft in the lower coast large enough to undertake the trip to San Nicolas. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid2692741 {\*\atrfend 419667516}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn 
{\*\annotation{\*\atnref 419667516}{\*\atndate 1194480520}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid2692741 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2692741 No boat available}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4919515 Days and week
s and months went by and those who at first had been most solicitous that assistance should be sent to the woman, began to salve their conscience[s] with the belief that, after all, it was impossible for the woman to reach the shore through the storm. The
 
Franciscan fathers, however, did not forget, and for years---as late as 1850---they offered a reward of $200 to any one who should find and bring the woman or child to Santa Barbara alive. In that year Thomas Jeffries visited the island, but on his return
 to the mainland reported that not a trace of the woman or child, living or dead, had been found. Time passed swiftly on, and soon the woman and child of San Nicolas became nothing more than a memory.
\par 
\par In July, 1853, an otter-hunting expedition visited San 
Nicolas. It was in command of George Nidiver, a prominent resident of Santa Barbara. The evening after the arrival, Nidiver and one of his men were strolling along the beach. It was a typical Southern California night---a night when the stars hang large a
nd low in the sky like Chinese lanterns and the moon is a great ball of amber. Nidiver stopped to light his pipe. He leaned over to scratch the match on his boot{\*\atrfstart 419667517}. The flaming match dropped from his hand:
\par 
\par "My God!" he exclaimed. "The woman of San Nicolas!"
\par 
\par Nidiver pointed to the print of a slender foot in the sand. Then he raised his voice, shouting in Spanish that friends were come to rescue her. Hours were spent in searching the island, but no trace of the woman was found. The next day Nidiver discovered 
a basket of rushes hanging in a tree; it contained bone needles, thread made of sinews, and a partially completed robe of birds' plumage, made of small squares neatly matched and sewed together. Nidiver scattered the things about, saying that if they were
 
picked up it would be proof that the owner had visited the spot. Inland they discovered several circular, roofless, inclosures, made of woven brush. Near these shelters were poles with dried meat hanging from elevated crosspieces. But there was no sight o
f the woman.
\par 
\par After several days of combing the island the otter-hunters gave up the search. There was no doubt in their minds that some one had been on the island recently. Either the woman or the child grown to womanhood had lived there, or perhaps both m
other and child had survived .After [sic] two months of hunting and fishing, the expedition prepared to return to the mainland. But Nidiver was not satisfied with the quest for the mysterious woman of San Nicolas. He declared his belief that the woman was
 
hiding from them. He swore an oath that if she were living he would find her and that if she were dead he would find the body, even if he had to scrape every inch of the island. The men of the expedition protested against the delay; they wanted to get hom
e. But Captain Nidiver was firm. He was going to solve the mystery of San Nicolas, he said, if it took the rest of his life.
\par 
\par So the whole force once more took up the hunt. After several days['] march, they found fresh footprints, and these led up into the 
cliffs where they were lost in the thick moss that covered the ground. The men climbed up the slippery cliffs and suddenly they came upon the woman crouching in terror behind the low woven-brush sides of her roofless hut. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 
