\par 
\par That was in the autumn of 1853. The people of Santa Barbara have for the most part forgotten the mystery of the unknown woman that came to them out of the sea one September evening almost three score years ago. Some of the old-timers remember the woman, a
n
d the Franciscan fathers will point out the grave of "Juana Marie" in the  shadow of the Mission tower; but who she was and what she was are as much a mystery today as they were when the Peor es Nada sailed away from San Nicolas in a tempest, leaving an I
ndian woman struggling in the foam-lashed waves that rolled with the roar of huge artillery on the rock-coast of the island.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448032 
